messages.content:
Para criar uma OCI Function com Terraform, você precisa provisionar os seguintes recursos:

1. **Log Group e Log** (pré-requisito para Functions):
```hcl
resource "oci_logging_log_group" "fn_log_group" {
  compartment_id = var.compartment_ocid
  display_name   = "fn-log-group"
}

resource "oci_logging_log" "fn_log" {
  display_name = "fn-invocation-log"
  log_group_id = oci_logging_log_group.fn_log_group.id
  is_enabled   = true
  log_type     = "SERVICE"
  configuration {
    source {
      category    = "all"
      resource    = ""
      source_type = "OCISERVICE"
    }
  }
  retention_duration = 30
}
```

2. **Application** (container onde as functions rodam):
```hcl
resource "oci_functions_application" "fn_app" {
  compartment_id = var.compartment_ocid
  display_name   = "my-fn-app"
  subnet_ids     = [var.subnet_ocid]
  config = {
    "LOG_GROUP_ID"     = oci_logging_log_group.fn_log_group.id
  }
  trace_config {
    domain_id = var.apm_domain_ocid
    is_enabled = true
  }
}
```

3. **Function** (a função em si):
```hcl
resource "oci_functions_function" "my_function" {
  application_id = oci_functions_application.fn_app.id
  display_name   = "process-data"
  image          = "<region>.ocir.io/<namespace>/process-data:latest"
  memory_in_mbs  = 256
  config = {
    "BUCKET_NAME" = "my-bucket"
  }
}
```

Pré-requisitos:
- A imagem Docker deve estar no OCIR (Oracle Container Image Registry)
- A subnet deve ser privada com acesso ao service gateway
- O dynamic group precisa de policy para ler imagens do OCIR

[MUTABLE] O memory_in_mbs pode variar entre 128MB e 3008MB.

Ref: https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Functions/Tasks/terraform-functions.htm

Para configurar um API Gateway que invoca OCI Functions, siga estes passos:

1. **Crie o API Gateway**:
```hcl
resource "oci_api_gateway_gateway" "my_gateway" {
  compartment_id = var.compartment_ocid
  display_name   = "my-api-gateway"
  subnet_id      = var.public_subnet_ocid
  response_cache_details {
    type = "NONE"
  }
}
```

2. **Defina a API Specification com function backend**:
```hcl
resource "oci_api_gateway_api" "my_api" {
  compartment_id = var.compartment_ocid
  gateway_id     = oci_api_gateway_gateway.my_gateway.id
  display_name   = "my-serverless-api"

  specification {
    logging_policies {
      access_log {
        is_enabled = true
      }
    }

    routes {
      path    = "/process"
      methods = ["POST"]
      backend {
        type                = "ORACLE_FUNCTIONS_BACKEND"
        function_id         = oci_functions_function.my_function.id
        connect_timeout_in_seconds = 10
      }
    }

    routes {
      path    = "/status"
      methods = ["GET"]
      backend {
        type = "HTTP_BACKEND"
        url  = "https://status.internal.example.com"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Pontos importantes:
- O tipo `ORACLE_FUNCTIONS_BACKEND` é específico para OCI Functions
- A subnet do gateway deve ser pública para acesso externo
- O connect_timeout padrão é 10 segundos, ajustável até 30s
- Para autenticação, adicione `authentication_policies` com `type = "NONE"` ou `"JWT_AUTHENTICATION"`

[MUTABLE] O timeout máximo pode variar conforme a região.

Ref: https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/APIGateway/Tasks/terraform-api-gateway.htm

Para configurar autenticação JWT no API Gateway do OCI via Terraform:

1. **Crie o API Gateway com JWT Authentication Policy**:
```hcl
resource "oci_api_gateway_api" "secure_api" {
  compartment_id = var.compartment_ocid
  gateway_id     = oci_api_gateway_gateway.my_gateway.id
  display_name   = "secure-api"

  specification {
    authentication_policies {
      type = "JWT_AUTHENTICATION"

      public_keys {
        type = "REMOTE"
        url  = "https://login.example.com/.well-known/jwks.json"
        cache_duration_in_seconds = 3600
      }

      token_header {
        name = "Authorization"
      }

      audiences = ["my-api-client"]
      issuers   = ["https://login.example.com"]
    }

    routes {
      path    = "/protected"
      methods = ["GET"]
      backend {
        type        = "ORACLE_FUNCTIONS_BACKEND"
        function_id = oci_functions_function.protected_fn.id
      }
      logging_policies {
        access_log {
          is_enabled = true
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

2. **Para múltiplos issuers ou validação customizada**:
```hcl
authentication_policies {
  type = "JWT_AUTHENTICATION"
  public_keys {
    type = "REMOTE"
    url  = "https://idp.example.com/oauth2/v1/keys"
  }
  audiences = ["audience-1", "audience-2"]
  issuers   = ["https://idp.example.com"]
  verification_key = {
    type = "REMOTE"
    url  = "https://idp.example.com/.well-known/openid-configuration"
  }
}
```

3. **Comparação com outros clouds**:
- AWS: Equivalente a API Gateway com Cognito Authorizer
- Azure: Equivalente a API Management com JWT Validation Policy

Pontos importantes:
- O JWKS endpoint deve ser acessível publicamente
- O cache_duration evita chamadas excessivas ao JWKS endpoint
- O token deve ser enviado no header `Authorization: Bearer <token>`

Ref: https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/APIGateway/Tasks/using-jwt-authentication.htm

Para gerenciar múltiplas versões de OCI Functions com Terraform, use a estratégia de aliases e imagens versionadas:

1. **Use tags de imagem versionadas no OCIR**:
```hcl
resource "oci_functions_function" "my_function_v1" {
  application_id = oci_functions_application.fn_app.id
  display_name   = "process-data-v1"
  image          = "${var.region}.ocir.io/${var.namespace}/process-data:1.0.0"
  memory_in_mbs  = 256
  config = {
    "VERSION" = "1.0.0"
  }
}

resource "oci_functions_function" "my_function_v2" {
  application_id = oci_functions_application.fn_app.id
  display_name   = "process-data-v2"
  image          = "${var.region}.ocir.io/${var.namespace}/process-data:2.0.0"
  memory_in_mbs  = 512
  config = {
    "VERSION" = "2.0.0"
  }
}
```

2. **Canary deployment com API Gateway**:
```hcl
resource "oci_api_gateway_api" "canary_api" {
  compartment_id = var.compartment_ocid
  gateway_id     = oci_api_gateway_gateway.my_gateway.id
  display_name   = "canary-api"

  specification {
    routes {
      path    = "/v1/process"
      methods = ["POST"]
      backend {
        type        = "ORACLE_FUNCTIONS_BACKEND"
        function_id = oci_functions_function.my_function_v1.id
      }
    }

    routes {
      path    = "/v2/process"
      methods = ["POST"]
      backend {
        type        = "ORACLE_FUNCTIONS_BACKEND"
        function_id = oci_functions_function.my_function_v2.id
      }
    }
  }
}
```

3. **Use variáveis para facilitar o rollout**:
```hcl
variable "function_version" {
  default = "2.0.0"
}

resource "oci_functions_function" "current_function" {
  application_id = oci_functions_application.fn_app.id
  display_name   = "process-data-current"
  image          = "${var.region}.ocir.io/${var.namespace}/process-data:${var.function_version}"
  memory_in_mbs  = 512
}
```

4. **Estratégia de rollout**:
- v1: produção estável
- v2: canary com 10% do tráfego
- Após validação, atualize a variável `function_version`
- Execute `terraform apply` para promover v2

[MUTABLE] O limite de funções por application pode variar.

Ref: https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Functions/Concepts/functionsoverview.htm

Para configurar rate limiting e throttling no API Gateway do OCI via Terraform:

1. **Rate limiting por rota**:
```hcl
resource "oci_api_gateway_api" "throttled_api" {
  compartment_id = var.compartment_ocid
  gateway_id     = oci_api_gateway_gateway.my_gateway.id
  display_name   = "throttled-api"

  specification {
    routes {
      path    = "/process"
      methods = ["POST"]
      backend {
        type        = "ORACLE_FUNCTIONS_BACKEND"
        function_id = oci_functions_function.my_function.id
      }

      rate_limiting {
        rate_key = "CLIENT_IP"
        rate_in_requests_per_second = 10
      }
    }

    routes {
      path    = "/health"
      methods = ["GET"]
      backend {
        type = "HTTP_BACKEND"
        url  = "https://health.internal.example.com"
      }
      # Sem rate limiting para health check
    }
  }
}
```

2. **Rate limiting global no gateway**:
```hcl
resource "oci_api_gateway_gateway" "my_gateway" {
  compartment_id = var.compartment_ocid
  display_name   = "my-api-gateway"
  subnet_id      = var.public_subnet_ocid

  response_cache_details {
    type = "NONE"
  }
}
```

3. **Opções de rate_key**:
- `CLIENT_IP`: Limita por IP do cliente
- `API_KEY`: Limita por chave de API (quando usando API key auth)

4. **Combinação com CORS para APIs públicas**:
```hcl
specification {
  cors {
    allowed_origins = ["https://app.example.com"]
    allowed_methods = ["GET", "POST"]
    allowed_headers = ["Content-Type", "Authorization"]
    max_age_in_seconds = 3600
  }

  routes {
    path    = "/api/{path*}"
    methods = ["GET", "POST", "PUT", "DELETE"]
    backend {
      type        = "ORACLE_FUNCTIONS_BACKEND"
      function_id = oci_functions_function.backend_fn.id
    }
    rate_limiting {
      rate_key = "CLIENT_IP"
      rate_in_requests_per_second = 5
    }
  }
}
```

5. **Comparação multi-cloud**:
- AWS: Equivalente ao API Gateway Usage Plans + Throttling
- Azure: Equivalente a API Management Rate Limit Policy

[MUTABLE] Os limites de rate podem variar por região e tipo de gateway.

Ref: https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/APIGateway/Tasks/ratelimiting.htm
